        <front>
            <title>Ozymandias</title>
            <author>Percy Bysshe Shelley</author>
        </front>
        <body>
            <octave>
                <quatrain>
                    <line><sb/>I met a traveller from an antique land,</line>
                    <line>Who said — “Two vast and trunkless legs of stone</line>
                    <line>Stand in the desart. ... Near them, on the sand,</line>
                    <line>Half sunk a shattered visage lies, whose frown,</line>
                </quatrain>
                <quatrain>
                    <link>And wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,</link>
                    <link>Tell that its sculptor well those passions read</link>
                    <link>Which yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,</link>
                    <link>The hand that mocked them, and the heart that fed;</link>
                </quatrain>
            </octave>
            <sestet>
                <tercet>
                    <link>And on the pedestal, these words appear:</link>
                    <link>My name is Ozymandias, King of Kings,</link>
                    <link>Look on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!</link>
                </tercet>
                <tercet>
                    <link>Nothing beside remains. Round the decay</link>
                    <line>Of that colossal Wreck,{phr] [phr}boundless and bare</line>
                    <line>The lone and level sands stretch far away.”</line>
                </tercet>
            </sestet>
        </body>
    </poem>
